messages.msgSnippet: Milt, I have seen some examples like your rat and daikon, but I can t recall any signed ones.  I have definitely seen other examples of the motif, but with a
messages.messageBody:
Milt,
I have seen some examples like your rat and daikon, but I can't recall any signed ones. I have definitely seen other examples of the motif, but with a rim. Hard to come up with an attribution based on the photo. It might not be a professionally made guard. The square cutout in the nakago ana is interesting. You see that on some Nanban guards (not that I think this one has anything to do with Nanban style).

The plate of the chidori guard looks like typical Tadatsugu work, but those are not typically decorated beyond the simple sukashi patterns. Tadatsugu was associated with the Umetada group, who of course did nunome zogan. The nunome here doesn't look to be very high quality, though. Maybe it's a later addition to jazz up the guard. I can't make out the surface carving very well in the photo, but I can see that it's there. I can't say that I've seen a combination exactly like that before. It's not typical of Tadatsugu work. I suppose it was done to give the surface some visual activity. It doesn't look deep enough to have been for inlay that is now missing. The boat in the reeds w/birds motif is quite common, but I haven't seen it combined with a plum blossom before. These may be successive layers of decoration that don't relate to one another beyond being present on the same tsuba.
Jim
P.S. I think that your Higo guards are Heianjo zogan.

-----
Jim,
I can't find similar example in books on the rat.( may be there's a reason
why ....... =) )

Also I have not seen the way they punched/incised pattern on the iron plate (
the chidori tsuba ), then did the flat inlays with subject matters ( chidori,
boat/reeds )totally unrelated to the pattern ( circle/curve lies ).
That basically is why I want to find out further...............

Milt

messages.messageBody:
First off I tried Milt's second link this morning and it worked fine. I
didn't even have to sign into Yahoo. It allowed me to view them as a guest, which
seems to be something new. Now my attempt to name the schools.

I have no idea what school the rat is from.

su1 is most likely a kyo piece see nicer much finer (thinner work)
@(Artswords.com the page was down for maintenance or I would have given the direct link)
or a copy of a kyo piece (the two ovoid anna are significant of a particular
school are they not? I'm too lazy to mull through all my texts right now to
find what school it is) I liked this piece but just didn't bid enough at the
end, oh well.

su3 is late owari (my guess without dimensions or thickness)

su5 could be Tosa or Shoami and a long shot would be Akasaka. I would have
to say it is most likely Tosa with all that fine engraving on it.

These are my guesses Milt, now you see how little I know. Would love to hear
what you think they are Milt. Also would like to hear from the experts to
learn a little something.

Lou
